  "prompt": "How do you say thank you in Arabic? Does it depend on who you're speaking to?",
  "response": "In Arabic, \"thank you\" is expressed as \"\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b\" (pronounced \"shukran\"). This phrase is widely understood across different Arabic-speaking countries. \n\nWhile \"shukran\" is generally appropriate for most situations, there are some dialectal variations and formalities you might consider depending on who you're speaking to:\n\n1. **Formality**: In more formal settings, you might say \"\u0623\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0643\" (pronounced \"ashkuruk\" for addressing a male, and \"ashkuruki\" for addressing a female\").\n  \n2. **Dialectal Differences**: In some dialects, you might hear variations like \"\u0645\u0631\u0633\u064a\" (pronounced \"mursee\"), borrowed from the French \"merci,\" which is especially common in Egypt.\n\n3. **Expressing Gratitude**: If you want to express deeper gratitude, you can say \"\u0634\u0643\u0631\u0627\u064b \u062c\u0632\u064a\u0644\u0627\u064b\" (pronounced \"shukran jazeelan\"), which means \"thank you very much.\"\n\nOverall, the basic expression \"shukran\" is universally understood and used across different contexts.",
